olumn":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Jupyter notebooks (and, often, a Python code library in which models are implemented) may be created and updated by different authors.\nHaving a separate repository for these models enables the authors to develop their own codes, avoiding requiring them to separately update a book implementation. It also avoids giving all authors editing access to the entire book content, which is not sustainable in the long run.","position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"key":"dQAqvL0Vde"}],"key":"Nvmy7P66hX"}],"key":"hAfTmDippo"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Different models require different sets of Python libraries.\nSome of these libraries are quite voluminous, so requiring a user of one model to install all libraries relevant to any of the other models is problematic.\nMoreover, Python libraries are updated and modified frequently; it is quite possible for different models in the book to require conflicting, incompatible versions of the same library.","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"key":"hTxYV06RRL"}],"key":"T028RULgn5"}],"key":"DncYoK4TZE"}],"key":"D3r7Qyo7bO"}],"key":"noN1nq93T1"}],"key":"uYiC4jdpfC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The easiest way to manage the libraries required to build the book on your own computer and to run the executable models in ","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"pkpguWn0gj"},{"type":"link","url":"https://jupyter.org/","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"chi